# Naming Conventions

## Core Principle

Every name must be self-explanatory without needing to trace the surrounding context. A reader should understand what a variable holds and what it belongs to from the name alone.

## Prefer Full Words

Prefer full descriptive words over abbreviations. Abbreviations save keystrokes but cost comprehension.

## Avoid Generic Placeholders

Do not use vague names that say nothing about what the value actually is:

❌ `data`, `info`, `value`, `item`, `temp`, `result`, `obj`, `val`, `thing`

✅ Use names that describe the domain concept: `userProfile`, `invoiceTotal`, `pendingMessages`

Loop indices (`i`, `j`) are acceptable only in trivially small, obvious loops.

## Booleans

Name booleans as a yes/no question answer:

✅ `isVisible`, `hasUnsavedChanges`, `canEdit`, `isLoading`, `hasFailed`

❌ `visible`, `unsavedChanges`, `editable`, `loading`

## Convey Ownership

When a value belongs to a specific entity, include that entity in the name:

✅ `userAvatarUrl`, `orderCreatedAt`, `sessionTokenExpiry`

❌ `avatarUrl`, `createdAt`, `expiry`
